---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import PageMeta from '@/components/PageMeta.astro';

const roadmapPdf = '/resource.html?path=source/08-external-references/uk-government/MHCLG-Home-Buying-and-Selling-Reform-Roadmap.pdf';
const govUk = 'https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/home-buying-and-selling-reform/outcome/home-buying-and-selling-reform-roadmap';
---
<Layout
  title="MHCLG Home Buying and Selling Reform Roadmap"
  description="The MHCLG Home Buying and Selling Reform Roadmap — the UK government's plan to make buying and selling a home quicker, cheaper and less stressful."
>
<PageMeta category="Strategy" variant="brand" updated="Updated 2026-06-25" />

      <h1>MHCLG Home Buying and Selling Reform Roadmap</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        The Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government (MHCLG) has published
        its <strong>Home Buying and Selling Reform Roadmap</strong> — the government's
        plan to make buying and selling a home quicker, cheaper and less stressful. It
        is the most authoritative current anchor for the property Smart Data initiative
        OPDA's standards work supports.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout--key">
        <div class="callout__label">Primary source</div>
        <p>
          The roadmap is the published outcome of the MHCLG <em>Home buying and selling
          reform</em> consultation. Read the full document below, or on gov.uk.
        </p>
        <p>
          <a class="resource-link" href={roadmapPdf}><code>MHCLG Home Buying and Selling Reform Roadmap (PDF, 62pp)</code></a>
          &nbsp;·&nbsp;
          <a href={govUk} target="_blank" rel="noopener">gov.uk — Home buying and selling reform roadmap</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="whyItMatters">Why it matters for OPDA</h2>
      <p>
        The roadmap sets the policy direction for digitising and de-risking the home
        buying and selling process. It reinforces the case for the data standards OPDA
        is authoring — the Property Data Trust Framework and its Smart Property evolution
        (SPDTF) — and for the wider UK Smart Data programme the property sector sits inside.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Upfront information.</strong> Standardised, machine-readable property data made available early in the transaction — exactly the gap OPDA's overlays (BASPI, the Law Society TA forms, HMLR searches) are designed to fill.</li>
        <li><strong>Data sharing and reuse.</strong> Trusted, provenance-bearing claims that move between parties without re-keying — the verifiable-claims model OPDA's standards adopt.</li>
        <li><strong>Digital identity.</strong> "Verify once, use many times" identity proofing aligned to the DVSTF (Digital Verification Services Trust Framework).</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="related">Related context</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/strategy/industrial-strategy">UK Industrial Strategy &amp; Smart Data</a> — the policy backdrop that names property as a priority Smart Data sector.</li>
        <li><a href="/strategy/reading-list">Strategy reading list</a> — the government and industry source documents, including this roadmap and the MHCLG consultation response.</li>
        <li><a href="/governance/uk-initiative">The UK government's Smart Property Data initiative</a> — how the five-tier initiative fits together.</li>
      </ul>
</Layout>
